snippet.textDisplay:
On a serious note, while I really want it to be a good movie, it worries me about the whole 'humans are the real monsters' cliche that turns so many other cool media with interesting worlds into just another 'humans vs humans, oh and there's some monsters sometimes I guess'. Not saying it's unrealistic or whatever (considering it's a movie about blind monsters wiping out everything without anyone having used their hearing against them until the family which hey, if you think about it, if it had to be someone then why not follow the story of those who found out?), just that I don't want it to turn super generic like so many other franchises or series have
But at least from what we have so far it doesn't seem like it'll lose focus on it's main antagonists (unlike certain other monster media lol)

snippet.textDisplay:
This film isn't so scary now that we know what the aliens look like and that they can be defeated pretty easily.

The last scene of the first film where they kill the Alien beastwith a simple shotgun shot to the head felt more like Diehard than the rest of the film, ruining it in my opinion.

They should have left the Alien monsters appearance a mystery (like in Bird Box) until this 2nd part or the last part if they're making a trilogy.

Probably a franchise though. Now the sequel has become only more star studded with Peaky Blinders Cilian Murphy to increase audience appeal.
